A [phase diagram](/Phase_diagram) is, essentially, a map. Not a particularly exciting one, mind you, but a map nonetheless, charting the rather predictable existence of a substance under varying conditions. In the realms of [physical chemistry](/Physical_chemistry), [engineering](/Engineering), [mineralogy](/Mineralogy), and [materials science](/Materials_science), these specific [charts](/Chart) serve to delineate the precise conditions—typically variations in [pressure](/Pressure) and [temperature](/Temperature), among other factors—at which distinct [thermodynamic phases](/Phase_(matter)) of a substance choose to manifest. More importantly, they illustrate the specific junctures where these states, such as the ever-so-distinct solid, liquid, or gaseous forms, can coexist in a state of tranquil [equilibrium](/Thermodynamic_equilibrium). It’s a testament to the universe’s meticulous, if somewhat uninspired, rule-following.

## Overview

The most fundamental elements etched onto any [phase diagram](/Phase_diagram) are what are rather prosaically termed [lines of equilibrium](/Phase_boundary), or more dramatically, [phase boundaries](/Phase_boundary). These aren't mere suggestions; they are the definitive borders, marking the exact confluence of conditions under which multiple phases of a given substance can serenely coexist. It is along these very lines that the drama of [phase transitions](/Phase_transition) unfolds, where a substance shifts its fundamental state. Curiously, or perhaps logically, [metastable](/Metastable) phases are conspicuously absent from these diagrams. They are, after all, fleeting, non-equilibrium states—mere temporary glitches in the grand scheme, and thus, deemed unworthy of permanent representation in a diagram dedicated to stability.

Then we encounter the [triple points](/Triple_point). These are the truly rare, almost cosmic coincidences on a [phase diagram](/Phase_diagram) where multiple lines of equilibrium converge and intersect. A [triple point](/Triple_point) signifies a singular set of conditions where a remarkable three distinct phases can simultaneously exist in perfect harmony. Consider, for instance, the [water phase diagram](/Water_(molecule)). It famously features a [triple point](/Triple_point) where solid ice, liquid water, and gaseous water vapor can all maintain a stable equilibrium. This particular marvel occurs at precisely 273.16&#160;[K](/Kelvin) (which is a chilling 0.01&#160;°C) and a [partial vapor pressure](/Partial_pressure) of 611.657&#160;[Pa](/Pascal_(unit)). When we speak of pressure on a pressure-temperature diagram, such as that for water, we're referring to the pressure exerted by the substance itself—environmental pressure for a condensed state, and the aforementioned [partial pressure](/Partial_pressure) when discussing its gaseous form.

For those navigating the complexities of solidification, two other critical concepts emerge: the [solidus](/Solidus_(chemistry)) and the [liquidus](/Liquidus). The [solidus](/Solidus_(chemistry)) represents the temperature threshold below which a substance definitively exists as a stable solid. Conversely, the [liquidus](/Liquidus) marks the temperature above which the substance is entirely and stably liquid. Intriguingly, there can exist a notable gap between these two lines. Within this interstitial region, the substance isn't quite solid, nor entirely liquid; instead, it manifests as a heterogeneous mixture of nascent crystals suspended within a liquid matrix—a state often unceremoniously referred to as a "[slurry](/Slurry)." Truly, a state of indecision.

Finally, a note for the engineers: [working fluids](/Working_fluids) are often classified and understood based on the unique geometry and contours of their respective [phase diagrams](/Phase_diagram), a practice that, I suppose, simplifies things for those who must actually *do* something with these substances.

## 2-dimensional diagrams

### Pressure vs temperature

The most straightforward, and frankly, least demanding, of the [phase diagrams](/Phase_diagram) are those that plot [pressure](/Pressure) against [temperature](/Temperature) for a single, uncomplicated substance. A prime example, and one often trotted out for illustrative purposes, is the [phase diagram for water](/Water_(molecule)). On these diagrams, the [axes](/Cartesian_coordinate_system) are, predictably, dedicated to [pressure](/Pressure) and [temperature](/Temperature), serving as the fundamental parameters that dictate a substance's state. The diagram then neatly carves out distinct regions corresponding to the [solid](/Solid), [liquid](/Liquid), and [gas](/Gas) phases, with the aforementioned [lines of equilibrium](/Phase_boundary) acting as the boundaries between them.

These curves on the [phase diagram](/Phase_diagram) aren't just arbitrary lines; they represent points where the [free energy](/Thermodynamic_free_energy) of the system, along with other derived thermodynamic properties, undergoes a rather abrupt, non-analytic change. This means their derivatives—how they change with respect to [temperature](/Temperature) or [pressure](/Pressure)—are discontinuous. For instance, the moment a block of ice melts into water, the [heat capacity](/Heat_capacity) of that system shifts dramatically. The expansive, open spaces between these lines, where the [free energy](/Thermodynamic_free_energy) behaves in an [analytic](/Analytic_function) and smooth fashion, correspond to regions where the substance exists solely in a single, unadulterated phase. These single-phase regions are, therefore, clearly demarcated by the boundaries where [phase transitions](/Phase_transition) are destined to occur.

One particularly intriguing feature, observed on the diagram to the right, is that the [phase boundary](/Phase_boundary) separating the liquid and gaseous states doesn't extend indefinitely into the thermodynamic ether. Instead, it culminates abruptly at a specific location on the [phase diagram](/Phase_diagram) known as the [critical point](/Critical_point_(thermodynamics)). This phenomenon elegantly illustrates that, under conditions of extremely elevated [temperatures](/Temperature) and [pressures](/Pressure), the liquid and gaseous states of a substance become utterly indistinguishable. They merge into a singular, bizarre entity known as a [supercritical fluid](/Supercritical_fluid), a state where the distinct characteristics of liquid and gas simply cease to exist. For [water](/Water_(molecule)), this point of ultimate ambiguity occurs at approximately T<sub>c</sub> = 647.096&#160;K (or 373.946&#160;°C), p<sub>c</sub> = 22.064&#160;MPa (equivalent to 217.75&#160;atm), and a density ρ<sub>c</sub> = 356&#160;kg/m<sup>3</sup>.

The very existence of this liquid–gas [critical point](/Critical_point_(thermodynamics)) introduces a subtle, almost philosophical, ambiguity in how we label these single-phase regions. While one typically traverses a [phase boundary](/Phase_boundary) when transitioning from a liquid to a gaseous state, it's theoretically possible to circumnavigate this boundary entirely by charting a course to the right of the [critical point](/Critical_point_(thermodynamics)). This implies that the liquid and gaseous phases can, under the right conditions, blend continuously into one another, without ever encountering a sharp transition. However, the solid–liquid [phase boundary](/Phase_boundary) is a far more stubborn affair; it can only terminate in a [critical point](/Critical_point_(thermodynamics)) if, and only if, the solid and liquid phases happen to possess the exact same underlying [symmetry group](/Symmetry_group)—a rather rare occurrence.

Regarding the [slope](/Slope) of the solid–liquid [phase boundary](/Phase_boundary), or the fusion curve, a fascinating divergence exists. For the vast majority of substances, this boundary exhibits a positive [slope](/Slope) on the [phase diagram](/Phase_diagram). This means that their [melting point](/Melting_point) reliably increases as [pressure](/Pressure) is applied. This behavior is observed whenever the solid phase of a substance is inherently [denser](/Density) than its liquid counterpart. The logic is straightforward: increasing [pressure](/Pressure) forces the molecules of the substance into closer proximity, thereby intensifying the effect of their [intermolecular forces](/Intermolecular_forces). Consequently, a higher [temperature](/Temperature) is required to supply the molecules with sufficient kinetic energy to overcome these strengthened forces and break free from the rigid lattice of the solid phase, allowing them to transition into the more fluid liquid state. A similar, though not identical, principle governs the dynamics of liquid–gas phase changes.

Yet, [water](/Water_(molecule)), in its characteristic defiance of convention, stands as a notable exception. Its solid-liquid boundary displays a negative [slope](/Slope), indicating that its [melting point](/Melting_point) *decreases* with increasing [pressure](/Pressure). This anomalous behavior stems from the well-known fact that ice (solid water) is less [dense](/Density) than liquid water—a phenomenon visibly demonstrated by ice cubes floating in a drink. At a molecular level, this lower density in ice is attributed to its more extensive and ordered network of [hydrogen bonds](/Hydrogen_bond), which necessitates a greater average separation between individual water molecules compared to the liquid state. Other substances that share this peculiar trait include [antimony](/Antimony) and [bismuth](/Bismuth), proving that [water](/Water_(molecule)) isn't entirely alone in its contrarian nature.

The universe, however, occasionally throws in another curveball. At extremely high [pressures](/Pressure), exceeding 50&#160;GPa (a staggering 500,000&#160;atm), [liquid nitrogen](/Liquid_nitrogen) undergoes an unexpected liquid-liquid phase transition, transforming into a polymeric form that surprisingly becomes [denser](/Density) than [solid nitrogen](/Solid_nitrogen) at the same [pressure](/Pressure). Under these extraordinary conditions, solid nitrogen would, counterintuitively, float in its own liquid.

The precise value of this [slope](/Slope), dP/dT, is elegantly quantified by the venerable [Clausius–Clapeyron equation](/Clausius%E2%80%93Clapeyron_relation) specifically tailored for fusion (melting) processes:

$$
{\frac {\mathrm {d} P}{\mathrm {d} T}}={\frac {\Delta H_{\text{fus}}}{T\,\Delta V_{\text{fus}}}}
$$

Here, ΔH<sub>fus</sub> represents the [heat of fusion](/Heat_of_fusion), which is an intrinsic property and always a positive value, indicating the energy required for melting. ΔV<sub>fus</sub>, conversely, denotes the change in volume that occurs during fusion. For the majority of substances, ΔV<sub>fus</sub> is positive, thereby yielding the positive [slope](/Slope) observed. However, for [water](/Water_(molecule)) and its rare brethren, ΔV<sub>fus</sub> is unequivocally negative, leading directly to the distinctive negative [slope](/Slope) on their [phase diagrams](/Phase_diagram). It's all just math, really.

### Other thermodynamic properties

Beyond the standard [temperature](/Temperature) and [pressure](/Pressure) axes, [phase diagrams](/Phase_diagram) are versatile enough to illustrate a broader spectrum of [thermodynamic properties](/Thermodynamic_property). These can include, but are not limited to, [specific volume](/Specific_volume), [specific enthalpy](/Specific_enthalpy), or even [entropy](/Entropy). For example, single-component graphs often depict [temperature](/Temperature) versus [specific entropy](/Entropy) (T vs. s) for substances like [water](/Water_(molecule)) or [steam](/Steam), or for a specific [refrigerant](/Refrigerant). Such diagrams are invaluable tools for visualizing and analyzing various [thermodynamic cycles](/Thermodynamic_cycle), from the theoretical perfection of a [Carnot cycle](/Carnot_cycle) to the practical applications of a [Rankine cycle](/Rankine_cycle) or a [vapor-compression refrigeration](/Vapor-compression_refrigeration) cycle.

The beauty of these two-dimensional diagrams lies in their adaptability: any two [thermodynamic quantities](/Thermodynamic_quantity) can be assigned to the horizontal and vertical axes. Any additional [thermodynamic quantities](/Thermodynamic_quantity) that one wishes to illustrate can then be represented as a series of incremental lines, which may be gracefully curved, rigidly straight, or an intriguing combination of both. Each of these "iso-lines" serves to represent the specific [thermodynamic quantity](/Thermodynamic_quantity) at a constant, defined value, providing a layered understanding of the system's behavior.

*   [enthalpy–entropy (h–s) diagram for steam](/Enthalpy%E2%80%93entropy_diagram)
*   [pressure–enthalpy (p–h) diagram for steam](/Pressure%E2%80%93enthalpy_diagram)
*   [temperature–entropy (T–s) diagram for steam](/Temperature%E2%80%93entropy_diagram)

## 3-dimensional diagrams

### p–v–T 3D diagram for fixed amount of pure material

For those who find two dimensions simply insufficient, it is indeed possible to conceptualize and even construct three-dimensional (3D) graphs that simultaneously display three distinct [thermodynamic quantities](/Thermodynamic_quantity). This is not groundbreaking, merely an extra axis. For a single-component system, a typical 3D [Cartesian coordinate system](/Cartesian_coordinate_system) graph might feature [temperature](/Temperature) (T) along one axis, [pressure](/Pressure) (p) along a second, and [specific volume](/Specific_volume) (v) along the third. Such a diagram is often rather unimaginatively referred to as a p–v–T diagram.

On these 3D constructs, the conditions under which equilibrium is maintained are depicted not merely as lines, but as curves etched onto a curved surface within the three-dimensional space. These surfaces delineate regions where the substance exists purely in the solid, liquid, or vapor phases, as well as areas where two phases—solid and liquid, solid and vapor, or liquid and vapor—can coexist in equilibrium. A particularly significant feature on this surface is the "triple line," which is precisely where the solid, liquid, and vapor phases can all simultaneously coexist in perfect equilibrium. The [critical point](/Critical_point_(thermodynamics)), that peculiar termination of the liquid-gas boundary, remains a singular point on this elaborate 3D surface, a stark reminder that some things just refuse to be stretched.

When one applies an [orthographic projection](/Orthographic_projection) to this 3D p–v–T graph, effectively flattening it by viewing it straight on, with [pressure](/Pressure) and [temperature](/Temperature) serving as the vertical and horizontal axes respectively, the entire intricate 3D plot collapses. The solid–vapor, solid–liquid, and liquid–vapor surfaces then simplify into the three familiar curved lines, all converging at the [triple point](/Triple_point)—which is, in essence, the flattened projection of the more expansive triple line. So, more dimensions just to confirm what we already knew from the 2D version.

## Binary phase diagrams

The complexity of [phase diagrams](/Phase_diagram) escalates rather dramatically, and perhaps predictably, when more than one pure component enters the system. In such scenarios, the [concentration](/Concentration) of each component becomes an additional, crucial variable to consider. Indeed, [phase diagrams](/Phase_diagram) can be constructed with more than two dimensions to illustrate the influence of an expanded array of variables on the phase behavior of a substance. These additional variables might include, for instance, the strength of an applied electrical or magnetic field, moving beyond the traditional [temperature](/Temperature), [pressure](/Pressure), and composition. They can also encompass substances that exhibit more than the conventional three states of matter.

One particularly common and vital type of [phase diagram](/Phase_diagram) is the one that plots [temperature](/Temperature) against the relative [concentrations](/Concentration) of two distinct substances within a binary mixture. This is known, quite logically, as a [binary phase diagram](/Binary_phase_diagram), as depicted to the right. Such a [mixture](/Mixture) can manifest in various forms, including a [solid solution](/Solid_solution), a [eutectic](/Eutectic_point), or a [peritectic](/Peritectic) system, among others, each yielding a distinctly different graphical representation. Another variant of the [binary phase diagram](/Binary_phase_diagram) is the boiling-point diagram, specifically designed for a mixture of two components. For two particular [volatile](/Volatility_(chemistry)) [chemical compounds](/Chemical_compound) at a defined [pressure](/Pressure), such as standard [atmospheric pressure](/Atmospheric_pressure), a boiling-point diagram illustrates the equilibrium relationship between the [vapor](/Vapor) (gas) compositions and the corresponding liquid compositions across a range of [temperatures](/Temperature). In its typical layout, [temperature](/Temperature) occupies the vertical axis, while the mixture's composition is spread along the horizontal axis.

### Boiling-point diagram

Consider a straightforward example: a two-component diagram illustrating components A and B within an "[ideal](/Ideal_solution)" solution. The construction of such a liquid-vapor [phase diagram](/Phase_diagram) fundamentally relies on the assumption of an [ideal liquid solution](/Ideal_solution) that dutifully obeys [Raoult's law](/Raoult%27s_law), coupled with an ideal gas mixture that adheres to [Dalton's law of partial pressures](/Dalton%27s_law_of_partial_pressure). A "tie line," a horizontal line drawn from the liquid phase to the gas phase at a constant [pressure](/Pressure), serves to indicate the precise compositions of both the liquid and gas phases that are in equilibrium at that specific [temperature](/Temperature) and [pressure](/Pressure). It's a simple visual tool for a complex interaction.

A simplified diagram, featuring hypothetical components 1 and 2 in a non-[azeotropic](/Azeotrope) mixture, is shown to the right. The presence of two distinct curved lines connecting the boiling points of the pure components immediately signals a critical insight: the composition of the vapor phase is typically *not* identical to the composition of the liquid phase with which it is in equilibrium. For a deeper dive into this fascinating interplay, one might consult the article on [Vapor–liquid equilibrium](/Vapor%E2%80%93liquid_equilibrium).

Beyond these basic types, [phase diagrams](/Phase_diagram) can incorporate a multitude of other specific features. Among these are "congruent points," which are special points where a solid phase undergoes a direct, unmediated transformation into a liquid phase. There is also the [peritectoid](/Peritectoid), a point that signifies the precise conditions under which two distinct solid phases will combine to form a single, new solid phase upon cooling. The inverse process, where a single solid phase transforms into two different solid phases during cooling, is known as the [eutectoid](/Eutectoid).

One particularly complex [phase diagram](/Phase_diagram), and one of immense technological importance, is that of the [iron](/Iron)–[carbon](/Carbon) system, especially for carbon concentrations less than 7% (the domain of [steel](/Steel)). This diagram is crucial for understanding the properties and processing of countless alloys.

It's worth noting that the x-axis of such a diagram, which represents the [concentration](/Concentration) variable of the mixture, is typically expressed in terms of [mole fraction](/Mole_fraction). This is the preferred measure because mixtures are often far from dilute, and their [density](/Density) as a function of [temperature](/Temperature) is usually not precisely known, rendering volume-based measures like [molarity](/Molarity) inadvisable and prone to error.

## Ternary phase diagrams

When a system involves three distinct components, it graduates to being called a [ternary system](/Ternary_system). At a constant [pressure](/Pressure), the maximum number of independent variables required to fully describe such a system becomes three: the [temperature](/Temperature) and two independent [concentration](/Concentration) values. To adequately represent these [ternary equilibria](/Ternary_equilibrium), a three-dimensional [phase diagram](/Phase_diagram) is, predictably, required. Often, such a diagram is constructed with the overall composition laid out on a horizontal plane, while the [temperature](/Temperature) axis projects perpendicularly from this plane. To represent the three-component composition in a visually coherent manner, an [equilateral triangle](/Equilateral_triangle) is employed, famously known as the [Gibbs triangle](/Gibbs_triangle) (see also [Ternary plot](/Ternary_plot)). It's a neat trick to cram three variables into a flat space.

*   [Gibbs triangle](/Gibbs_triangle)
*   [Space phase diagram of a ternary system](/Ternary_system)

The [temperature](/Temperature) scale is then plotted along an axis that stands perpendicular to this composition triangle, creating a spatial model of the [ternary phase diagram](/Ternary_phase_diagram) that resembles a right-triangular prism. The three sides of this prism inherently represent the corresponding binary systems: A-B, B-C, and A-C, each a simpler, two-component interaction.

However, for practical purposes, the most common and effective methods used to present [phase equilibria](/Phase_equilibrium) in a [ternary system](/Ternary_system) typically involve:
1.  **Projections:** Displaying the liquidus, solidus, and solvus surfaces as projections onto the foundational concentration triangle (ABC). This flattens the 3D information into a more manageable 2D view.
2.  **Isothermal sections:** These are cross-sections of the 3D diagram taken at a constant [temperature](/Temperature), providing a snapshot of the phase relationships at a specific thermal condition.
3.  **Vertical sections:** These are cross-sections taken along a specific composition path at varying [temperatures](/Temperature), offering insights into how phases evolve as [temperature](/Temperature) changes for a fixed ratio of two components.

## Crystals

The universe, in its infinite complexity, often presents substances that are not content with a simple solid, liquid, or gas existence. [Polymorphic](/Polymorphism_(materials_science)) and [polyamorphic](/Polyamorphism) substances, for instance, exhibit multiple distinct [crystal](/Crystal) structures or various [amorphous](/Amorphous) phases. These varied forms can be charted and understood in a manner analogous to how solid, liquid, and gaseous phases are represented on a [phase diagram](/Phase_diagram).

A prime example of this intricate behavior is seen in [water](/Water_(molecule)) itself. A [log-lin](/Semi-log_plot) [pressure](/Pressure)–[temperature](/Temperature) [phase diagram](/Phase_diagram) for [water](/Water_(molecule)) will reveal an astonishing array of different [ice phases](/Phases_of_ice), each denoted by [Roman numerals](/Roman_numeral), illustrating how even a seemingly simple solid can adopt numerous crystalline arrangements under varying conditions. It’s almost as if it can’t make up its mind.

## Mesophases

Some organic materials, not quite solid and not quite liquid, decide to occupy an interesting intermediate ground. These substances transition through states that exist between the conventional solid and liquid phases, and these peculiar states are known as [mesophases](/Mesophase). These aren't merely scientific curiosities; considerable attention has been directed towards [mesophases](/Mesophase) due to their practical applications. They are, notably, the enabling technology behind modern [display devices](/Display_device) and have achieved significant commercial importance through what is universally recognized as [liquid-crystal](/Liquid_crystal) technology. Consequently, [phase diagrams](/Phase_diagram) are indispensable tools for mapping and understanding the specific conditions under which these fascinating [mesophases](/Mesophase) occur and exist. The universe, it seems, has a fondness for ambiguity.

